B. H. Tan — Filecoin token analytics

Token analytics

The goal of this project was to analyze in detail transactions occurring in the Filecoin network, and answer questions such as

  • Which countries/regions produce token?
  • How is the token distributed by stakeholder?
  • How does token flow from and between stakeholders?
  • What behavioural patterns characterise each group of stakeholders?

The project was delivered through interactive charts on Plotly.

1 Circulating supply

 

1a Breakdown by archetype

Here we show the breakdown of both circulating supply (left) and total supply (right) by archetype. Note the difference between the two definitions. The total supply is a measure of all available token in the network, whether or not it is available for transaction. Clearly, the majority of the 1.5 billion token is currently held in reserve.

In contrast, the circulating supply is the total balance of all actors in the network, less any locked funds. SAFT and other investment accounts have token withheld over a set vesting period, while storage providers have a portion of their rewards locked and they also pay an initial pledge to commit sectors to the network.

1b Evolution of circulating supply by archetype

The proportion of exchanges and retail wallets has grown in time, while the contribution of special accounts has diminished.

2 Account balances

 

Most accounts are retail wallets, so the overall distribution of account balance hews closely to that of retail wallets. It is evident in the chart here that the typical account balances are smallest (100-1000 FIL) for retail wallets and storage providers, intermediate (1000-10000 FIL) for multisig, Protocol Labs and SAFT accounts, and large (> 1 million) for exchanges.

3 Token flow

 

3a An overview of token flow

Before drilling down into individual actors on the network here we present some aggregate statistics across the network. The vast majority of actors have fewer than 1 transaction per day and move less than 1 FIL per day. Activity in terms of FIL transacted per day obeys a rough power law, with just a handful of actors transacting more than 100,000 FIL per day. Finally, the mean FIL moved per transaction is about 10 FIL.

 

3b Token flow breakdown by archetype

This chart shows token outflow and inflow for each major archetype per day. Interestingly, each archetype exhibits large spikes at different days, most likely coinciding with market movements or major changes to the network.

4a Overall statistics of SAFT accounts

5 Geolocation

 

5a Geolocation coverage of miners

In the chain there are nearly 600,000 miners recorded. However, only about 4000 of them have any discernible activity. We set a low bar for activity — a miner is active if it has ever produced a block. Interestingly, while inactive miners almost never register an IP address, 55% of active miners actually do register an IP address. The remaining 45% can be geolocated by synthetic locations.

5b Regional breakdown of miner balance

A large proportion (nearly 50%) of balance in miner accounts is held in Asia. In this analysis, each miner ID can be assigned more than one locale — these miners are assigned "multi-region".

5c Country breakdown of miner balance

5d Global heatmap of mining activity

Where are the world's hot spots of mining activity? This map shows the geographic location of every geolocatable miner as a geographic heatmap with a common brightness scale across the world, coloured by the rewards mined. Many global cities, big and small, are represented here.

The network of transactions in Filecoin

We construct a transaction network by joining two actors by an edge if they transfer token to each other. Each actor occupies a node in the network. The full transaction network consists of 3 million nodes and is tricky to plot out, let alone analyze.

To overcome this difficulty, we use a procedure called principal component analysis to group all of the nodes by their transactional behaviour. In the chart below, the little bubbles are colored by the sum of outgoing transactions and sized by either account balance or value spent. These points represent just 3,000 of the 3 million nodes.

  • Fringe. These nodes are at the very edge of the network, with few interactions with other parties. Think of it as a quiet coastal village.
  • Hub. These nodes are important and have transactions with many other parties. Analogous to a major financial capital.
  • Bridge. These nodes are important in a network centrality sense (they connect hubs) but have few transactions themselves. Analogous to a small town that joins two major cities.
  • Outpost. These nodes have many transactions but are not important to the overall network. Analogous to a political capital in a country with a financial capital, the Berlin to Frankfurt.

Archetype labelling with limited data

Apart from simply visualizing network structure, this analysis allows us to exhaustively search and label archetypes even when we have limited or no labelled data. For example, we would like to find out how many of the actors are related to exchanges, but only have a list of 13 of them (red points), which we have obtained by manually depositing token into major exchanges. These points occupy a very localised region in the PCA space, as they behave similarly. By finding which of the 3 million nodes fall into the space marked out by the sample points, we have found all 300 actors associated with major exchanges.
